Harley-Davidson motorcycles bring heart-thumping adventure, life-changing freedom and a bit of rebellion into the lives of people around the world. But whether you were born to be wild – or mild – makes no difference at the Harley-Davidson Museum in Milwaukee, Wisconsin. Much more than a nostalgia trip for motorcycle enthusiasts, the Museum offers a glimpse of American history and culture like you’ve never seen it before – through the successes and trials of an iconic American Motor company. This is Harley heaven. Everything you could want to know about the company is displayed from its humble beginnings in a shed to the disastrous AMF years to the worldwide powerhouse of today. The top floor is devoted to the beginnings of the company. It is simply amazing the number of bikes they have on display here. It was also amazing to see the first generation Harley's fully restored and even more amazing that people Actually road them. The lower level continued the Harley story taking you into Harley in films and the end of the tour features a section where you can climb atop various Harleys in history. At D&D we love Harley-Davidson motorcycles. If you are interested in improving the tone and performance of your bike then check us out at www.danddexhaust.com

This amazing chopper was built by Ron Finch of nearby Pontiac, at his Finch's Custom Styled Cycles shop. He has been building unique custom motorcycles for decades. This one was built for an art show in Grand Rapids, Michigan which had over 1500 accepted entries. Ron is quite proud that his Chopper @ Large was in the top 100 among the peoples' choice awards. Finch's Customs Visit to the renowned Woodward Dream Cruise on Friday, August 16, 2013. While the official "cruise day" (30,000 or more cruise vehicles) is Saturday, Dream Cruise events take place for the whole week prior along sixteen miles of Woodward Avenue from the city limits of Detroit to the city of Pontiac. While Friday predates the official cruise day, by the time we left at approx. 4 pm, Woodward was thronged with cruisers and the regular daily traffic moving at a glacial pace. Laid flat on my back for this shot. Surprised I'm not still laying there!

In the cult movie Easy Rider, the Chopper motorcycle ridden by Wyatt, played by Peter Fonda, is known as Captain America and its fuel tank painted with the US flag. With his companion Billy (Dennis Hopper), Wyatt sets out to leave his life doing motorcycle stunts with a travelling circus. Like many young men of the time, Hannover Harley-Davidson dealer Matthias Korte's life was heavily influenced by the film, and his Captain America lookalike is now one of his most prized possessions. He built it in 1993 from the remains of a 1948 Panhead 1200, with no front brake, just like the film bike. ---------- Goodwood Festival of Speed 2009 P7032447

The El Fo Fitty gathers a crowd everywhere it goes, especially at Alice’s Restaurant. The Dirtbag Challenge is a bike build off for real working people. You get thirty days to build a chopper, you can’t spend more than $1,000 (including the bike), and you have to complete a 100 mile ride on it. Only the builders get to vote for the winners (except the People’s Choice Award). The event is more like the coolest party you’ll ever attend. An incredibly diverse crowd, food and beer, loud music, burnouts – total chaos! More fun than is humanly possible with the best and truest friends you’ll ever have. The website thedirtbagchallenge.com/ describes it best: “The Dirtbag Challenge started as a reaction to the increasing perception that a custom motorcycle had to be expensive. There is a belief that custom bikes are the exclusive right of rich pretty boys and media personalities, rolling around on cookie cutter motorcycles that cost the same as a small family home. Well that’s bullshit. The Dirtbag Challenge is a low rent chopper build-off, featuring real world bikes for riding in the real world. More than that, at the heart of it is a need to do your own thing, to break away from the same old mainstream ideals. Dirtbag is about doing things your own way – without anyone’s approval, without anyone’s permission. Build the bike you want, live the life you choose. If we can do it, so can you.” Comments and critiques are welcome. Contact biker1337@yahoo.com to use this image.

photo.title: 1947 Custom Indian Chief, Gastown Motorcycle Show n' Shine 2010 Had Hell Angels and Bike Enthusiasts Ogling

description._content: The Gastown Motorcycle Show n' Shine took place on Aug 15, 2010 along Vancouver’s Water Street between Richards and Carall. There were cruisers, sport bikes, fat boys, customs, choppers, softtails, vintage, Euro, Japanese, Americans, rat bikes, tour bikes, sidecars, drag bikes, electric scooters for a sustainable future and more. For $20 or less, you could bring your bike to the show and have judges looked it over to see if yours deserved the first prize. Several manufacturers had their display on site and they made sure that you know who they are and where they come from. Same with some in the crowd. Quite a few wore colors on their vest as well. The Hells Angels, bike enthusiast and causal onlookers rub shoulder with each other and ogled the same thing - motorcycles. Thousands jammed the Gastown streets to enjoy this free event organized by the B.C. Coalition of Motorcyclists that is the biggest annual bike show in town. The only thing you won’t find was the revving noise of the bike engines. This section of Gastown that was once Gassy Jack Deighton’s old haunts was blocked off to traffic completely to facilitate the bike show and to provide limited parking for bikers who drove their motorcycles to the show. [Photos by Ray Van Eng ] www.vancouver21.com

Maryland State Fairgrounds played host to one of the largest motorcycle shows on the east coast which is known as the Timonium Motorcycle Show (TMS). Even though the festivities take place during the height of winter, it surely looks like summer once you enter the building. Motorcycle enthusiasts, builders, enthusiasts and patrons make the trek to gaze over a cadre of custom sportbikes, baggers, choppers, drag bikes, vintage cycles and antiques of all makes from around the country. With the TMS attendance rising each year, Maryland State Fairgrounds housed over 45,000 showgoers over the 3-day bike festival.

description._content:
triumph chopper: very unique TR6SC only 346 made in 1965!
sc=street competition...
lower gear ratio for faster takeoff?
I understand that all "SC" units were manufactured from '61-'66 and all went to Johnson Motors , matching frame and engine..
according the the Trophy Bible, the TR6SC's were made from1964 to 1966.
There were 60 made 1n 1964, 346 in 1965, & 260 in 1966.
The engines in the SC models were the same as those in the Trophy (TR6R), other than having a lower gear ratio and ET ignition. What is unique about the SC line are other bits, like special valving in the forks, folding foot pegs, 2.5 gallon slimline tank, lack of a tach, and Dunlop Trials Universal tires.
East coast models came equipped with lights, while west coast models, which were the predecessor to the TT Special, had none.

Friday night in Novi, MI. The Ultimate Builder starts Friday afternoon and runs through Sunday night. 


Enter your custom bike into the Progressive® International Motorcycle Shows® Ultimate Builder Custom Bike Show and pitch it against the best builders in the country. The UBCBS is an affiliate competition to the AMD World Championship of Custom Bike Building. Professional and amateur custom builders of choppers, cruisers and sportbikes are invited to enter their bikes into the competition and judge each other’s work. There will be 11 individual rounds of the Ultimate Builder Custom Bike Show nationwide. 

American Championship

The American Championship of custom bike building will be held at the Daytona Progressive International Motorcycle Show held during Daytona Bike Week, March 9-12, 2011. This elite competition is for the ultimate builders of custom bikes in the United States and neighboring countries and will crown the definitive American Champions in their respective classes. The American Championship is an affiliate competition to the AMD World Championship of Custom Bike Building.

The American Championship will also include an individual photo shoot by a professional photographer of each bike entered into the competition. Each builder/bike owner will receive a CD of photos taken during the event of themselves and their bikes.

Judged Custom Bike Classes

Free Style: Any motorcycle frame configuration or drivetrain combination. Your imagination is the only restriction. Must run and stop.

Modified Harley: Must have Harley manufactured frame and engine cases. Frame must maintain stock configuration so modifications are limited to smoothing ie; molding welds and joints, welding in filler panels or cutting excess tabs. Swingarm kits and fat tire conversions are acceptable .

Performance Custom: Race inspired styling with performance enhancing engine modifications. Any motorcycle frame configuration and drivetrain combination. Judging will be focused around drag racing ie; strtched out ‘Busa, Bonneville racers and highly modified sportbikes. 

The Mob Rules

The masses can’t be kept silent and a fourth award will be given at each round of the UBCBS and the American Championship, chosen by the mob. This is essentially a “people’s choice” award, and the people can be fickle. The winner of the Mob Rules trophy could be a bike built in a state-of-the-art machine shop, or a two car garage at the end of a cul-de-sac. It’s all up to them.

description._content:
With just a few hours to go before opening to the public, it is set-up day at the 8th annual AMD World Championship of Custom Bike Building, with builders from all over the world uncrating their bikes and the show taking shape in Champions Hall at 3rd/Lazelle in downtown Sturgis, South Dakota.

Again co-located at the Sturgis Rally with Harley-Davidson, the show opens at 9.00am (MDT) on Sunday 7th August, and runs for four days, with the results of Tuesday's competitor judging being unveiled at the awards ceremony at 3.00pm on Wednesday 10th.


The culmination of a year-round cycle of affiliate events worldwide, the 80 or so bikes that are expected to compete in the four World Championship classes are the cream of a program that has seen some 5,000 bikes in total compete at events that have had over 2 million visitors in the past 12 months, in markets with some 65 million road registered motorcycles, and close to 1 billion consumers in total.

description._content: The 2012 69 Chopper called Filigree made its debut at the 2011 Ultimate Builder Custom Bike Show in Dallas, Tx. (www.ultimatebuilderbikeshow.com) The chopper was built by Brass Balls Bobbers and sports several world-class components that enhance the handling and performance. The heart of the bike is a custom-built engine by Crazy Horse Motorcycles, primary from Evil Engineering, electrics from Accel, wiring and speedo from Wire-Plus, gas cap, headlight and rear light form Crime Scene Choppers and controls from Excel. The paint is based on the original Brass Balls Tattoo bike where the raw metal was clear coated. Brass Balls used candy blue and pin striped filigree. The paint contrasts nicely with the nickel-plated frame. The bike delivers a soul-satisfying experience and the deep rumble from the 100ci Crazy Horse engine, which makes its presence known through a D&D Bob Cat exhaust system from D&D Performance Enterprises.

Wheels Through Time Museum is home to the world’s premier collection of rare American Vintage Motorcycles. photo.title: 2010 Dragon Electric Scooters, Gastown Motorcycle Show n' Shine 2010 Had Hell Angels and Bike Enthusiasts Ogling

description._content: The Gastown Motorcycle Show n' Shine took place on Aug 15, 2010 along Vancouver’s Water Street between Richards and Carall. There were cruisers, sport bikes, fat boys, customs, choppers, softtails, vintage, Euro, Japanese, Americans, rat bikes, tour bikes, sidecars, drag bikes, electric scooters for a sustainable future and more. For $20 or less, you could bring your bike to the show and have judges looked it over to see if yours deserved the first prize. Several manufacturers had their display on site and they made sure that you know who they are and where they come from. Same with some in the crowd. Quite a few wore colors on their vest as well. The Hells Angels, bike enthusiast and causal onlookers rub shoulder with each other and ogled the same thing - motorcycles. Thousands jammed the Gastown streets to enjoy this free event organized by the B.C. Coalition of Motorcyclists that is the biggest annual bike show in town. The only thing you won’t find was the revving noise of the bike engines. This section of Gastown that was once Gassy Jack Deighton’s old haunts was blocked off to traffic completely to facilitate the bike show and to provide limited parking for bikers who drove their motorcycles to the show. photo.title: Jaybrake’s Made In America Controls and Brake System Featured on The Horse Backstreet Choppers Magazine / Brass Balls / Bikernet.com Giveaway Chopper.

description._content: Jaybrake’s Made In America Controls and Brake System Featured on The Horse Backstreet Choppers Magazine / Brass Balls / Bikernet.com Giveaway Chopper. Darwin Motorcycles, manufacturer of Brass Balls Bobbers & Choppers, announced today that Jaybrake will provide their entire series of Made in America custom set of quad calipers for both front and rear, classic forward controls with dovetail pegs and J-series hand controls for The Horse Backstreet Choppers Magazine / Brass Balls / Bikernet.com Giveaway Chopper. Jaybrake is a world class ISO and TUV certified machining facility with the resources to take an idea quickly through design stage, engineering, prototyping and into final assembly. “I have been looking at the Jaybrake product line and really like the craftsmanship that I see,” explained Dar Holdsworth, Brass Balls Bobbers and Choppers’ BossMan. “I was excited that Keith Horschel, Jay Brainard and the executive team at Jaybrake decided to support our project.” The Horse Backstreet Choppers Magazine / Brass Balls / Bikernet.com Giveaway Chopper contains unique, American made components that make a statement about the innovation, design and craftsmanship of American manufacturers. The 69 Chopper is an award-winning production motorcycle that placed 3rd in the AMD World Championship of Custom Bike Building. “We are excited to support The Horse Backstreet Choppers Magazine / Brass Balls / Bikernet.com Giveaway Chopper project and to work with Dar Holdsworth, a top chopper designer,” said Keith Horschel, HBP-Sales and Marketing. “We like the look of this compact hard tail chopper and look forward to seeing the bike given away at next year’s Smoke Out East.” The Horse Backstreet Choppers Magazine and Bikernet.com are showcasing the build and reporting on the style of bikes that their readers enjoy and like to ride. Choppers like the ones that roll out of Darwin Motorcycles are light weight, fast and provide serious fun. So check out the build and enter to win the 69 Chopper. Details are at www.winthechopper.com. Sponsors of The Horse Backstreet Choppers Magazine / Brass Balls / Bikernet.com Giveaway Chopper include Aeromach, Jaybrake, Wire Plus Powersports Electronics, Biker Pros, D&D Performance Enterprises, Bikernet.com, Spectro, Custom Chrome and Paucho. About Jaybrake Jaybrake is a leader in the manufacturing of performance motorcycle parts and accessories directed towards the American V-twin market. Brake calipers, forward foot controls, handlebar controls, foot pegs, grips, switch housing and other handlebar accessories are just some of the billet aluminum components Jaybrake is known for. Established in 1981 by Jay Brainard, the company has grown from a one man operation in a garage on the family farm to part of an 82,000 square foot state-of-the-art-facility. Living by the two slogans of “made in the USA” and “we make it” truly is what makes Jaybrake a company with small hometown values and pride of craftsmanship.

Enter your custom bike into the Progressive® International Motorcycle Shows® Ultimate Builder Custom Bike Show and pitch it against the best builders in the country. The UBCBS is an affiliate competition to the AMD World Championship of Custom Bike Building. Professional and amateur custom builders of choppers, cruisers and sportbikes are invited to enter their bikes into the competition and judge each other’s work. There will be 11 individual rounds of the Ultimate Builder Custom Bike Show nationwide. 

American Championship

The American Championship of custom bike building will be held at the Daytona Progressive International Motorcycle Show held during Daytona Bike Week, March 9-12, 2011. This elite competition is for the ultimate builders of custom bikes in the United States and neighboring countries and will crown the definitive American Champions in their respective classes. The American Championship is an affiliate competition to the AMD World Championship of Custom Bike Building.

The American Championship will also include an individual photo shoot by a professional photographer of each bike entered into the competition. Each builder/bike owner will receive a CD of photos taken during the event of themselves and their bikes.

Judged Custom Bike Classes

Free Style: Any motorcycle frame configuration or drivetrain combination. Your imagination is the only restriction. Must run and stop.

Modified Harley: Must have Harley manufactured frame and engine cases. Frame must maintain stock configuration so modifications are limited to smoothing ie; molding welds and joints, welding in filler panels or cutting excess tabs. Swingarm kits and fat tire conversions are acceptable .

Performance Custom: Race inspired styling with performance enhancing engine modifications. Any motorcycle frame configuration and drivetrain combination. Judging will be focused around drag racing ie; strtched out ‘Busa, Bonneville racers and highly modified sportbikes. 

The Mob Rules

The masses can’t be kept silent and a fourth award will be given at each round of the UBCBS and the American Championship, chosen by the mob. This is essentially a “people’s choice” award, and the people can be fickle. The winner of the Mob Rules trophy could be a bike built in a state-of-the-art machine shop, or a two car garage at the end of a cul-de-sac. It’s all up to them.

Each and every year Maryland State Fairgrounds plays host to one of the largest motorcycle shows on the east coast which is known as the Timonium Motorcycle Show (TMS). Enthusiasts, builders, and patrons from all over come to witness the bevy of custom sportbikes, baggers, choppers, drag bikes, vintage cycles and antiques of every make throughout the country. With the TMS attendance rising annually the 3-day bike festival housed over 45,000 showgoers for 2016!

description._content:
San Antonio’s Sal DiGiacomo Wins May’s drawing for the “Military Bobber for the Troops Raffle” and takes home a Torian Chopper Leathers’ 11 pocket vest and Bikernet.com t-shirt.

For just $10 smacks you could take home a $30,000 custom motorcycle from Brass Balls Bobbers. Click here to enter.

It is the least expensive way to put a custom motorcycle in your garage.


    “I appreciate the Torian vest as it fits like a glove and is just the ticket for my Modern Classic Honda 500 Turbo,” explained DiGiacomo. “The Intrepid Wounded Heros Fund is an organization that is really helping out and I am proud to support the organization & Brass Balls Choppers.”

The Intrepid Fallen Heros Fund – Brass Balls is raffling off the Military Bobber with the proceeds going to the Intrepid Fallen Heros Fund.

This fund is helping the returning veterans that have sustained head injuries. It is a way for you to support the troops and feel good at the same time.


    “The goal of Win the Military Bobber for the Troops Raffle is to raise the necessary funds for veterans suffering from traumatic brain injury (TBI) and psychological health issues.” “Now individuals that support the military can participate in this event online and may just come home with a custom Bobber.”
